column168: CHECKED A GREEN CLOTH DUFFEL BAG IN AMARILLO ON THE MORNING OF JANUARY 3, 1 985, BAGGAGE TAG 66-14-25-19.  IT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY LEARNED THAT THE BAG CON TAINED A ONE GALLON CONTAINER, LABELED DIAZINON PACKED IN A CLEAR PLASTIC B AG AND A BURGESS ELECTRIC INSERT FOGGER IN THE MANUFACTURER'S CARTON, IN AD DITION TO OTHER ITEMS.  THE REGULATED MATERIAL WAS NOT DECLARED BY THE PASS ENGER OR IT WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN CARRIED BY SOUTHWEST AIRLINES.  AT AMARILLO , THE RAMP AGENT WAS FINISHING LOADING BAGS INTO THE FORWARD CARGO BIN OF F LIGHT 602 AIRCRAFT NUMBER N82SW WHEN HE BECAME AWARE OF AN ODOR WHEN HE CHE CKED HE OBSERVED A FLUID LEAKING FROM THE BAG, COVERING AN AREA BETWEEN THE WEBBING OF FA AND FC.  THE BAG WAS REMOVED AND CHECKED BY THE RAMP SUPERVI SOR, WHO NOTICED THAT IT HAD A FAINT ODOR OF BUG SPRAY BUT WAS NO LONGER LE AKING.  THE BAG WAS RELOADED AND THE FLIGHT DISPATCHED TO ALBUQUERQUE.  AFT ER THE DEPARTURE, ALBUQUERQUE WAS NOTIFIED THAT A BAG HAD LEAKED IN THE FOR WARD BIN AND THAT IT WAS THOUGHT TO HAVE STOPPED LEAKING.  ON ARRIVAL AT AL BUQUERQUE, ALL BAGS WERE REMOVED IN AN ATTEMPT TO LOCATE THE BAG THAT HAD L EAKED.  THE STATION WAS UNABLE TO FIND A SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND A DECISION TO RELOAD AND DISPATCH THE FLIGHTS WAS MADE.  ABOUT 15 MINUTES AFTER DEPART URE FROM ALBUQUERQUE, AGENT BRUCE STONE BEGAN TO SHOW SIGNS OF DIZZINESS AN D NAUSEA.  HE WAS TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AT ONE OF LOCAL HOSPITALS.  A LBUQUERQUE NOTIFIED PHOENIX AND THE GENERAL OFFICE IN DALLAS OF THE INCIDENT.  THE DECISION TO INSPECT AND DETERMINE THE SUBSTANCE ON ARRIVAL AT PHOENIX WAS MADE BY THE GENERAL OFFICE.  ON ARRIVAL AT PHOENIX, THE PHOENIX FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE IN CLEANING UP THE FORWARD BIN.  THE LIQUID WAS A PESTICIDE DIAZINON 4E.  THIRTY-SIX BAGS HAD THE LIQUID ON THEM. THE BAG CONTAINING THE ONE-GALLON CONTAINER OF DIAZINON AND THE FOGGER WAS SOAKED THRU.  EIGHT OF THE BAGS REQUIRED DISPOSAL AND THE REMAINING WERE CLEANED AND RETURNED TO CUSTOMERS.
